what is the rate limit of chutes api?

By default, 30 requests per minute. If the model is not on open router, it is double. If the account is a paid user (meaning they don't have the free_account bit set), that value is multiplied by 3 (so it could be 30 * 2 * 3 if also not on openrouter).
We currently have to manually increase rate limits but soon it will be based on payment history and/or alpha stake on the coldkey associated with the account probably.

FYI some of the instances have been returning absolutely nothing over time, not even a `data: [DONE]` in the stream (I believe all of them were SGLang backend, need to dig deeper), which may have caused weird discrepancies in scoring. This happened in the past a bit to me (not chutes related, just using sglang elsewhere), so I suspect that's the culprit but still digging.

I put in a new exception to detect these empty stream responses and retry on a difference instance (which will also overtime trigger the auto-deletion of the instance): https://github.com/rayonlabs/chutes-api/commit/5d87dcce97e8ce5dcb1b96d5b7a1d145931736b2

I’m a content creator, and I’m very interested in Bittensor’s subnets, but I’m having trouble understanding the differences between NineteenAI and Chutes. It would really help me if you could answer my questions! 🙂

What is the difference between Chutes and Nineteen? What is the purpose of the miners on Chutes?

Both of these subnets seem to offer similar inference services and provide an API, so why did Rayon Labs create two separate subnets?
@namoray 🫶🏻
@namoray , @Victor VL  creates excellent content, and high-quality content like this is very rare for the French-speaking community. I hope you'll take a few moments to answer his questions.

@namoray is not available at the moment but he will chime in as soon as he can as well, but in the meantime I can give an answer from my perspective.

Nineteen is an inference subnet that provides extremely fast and reliable inference for a specific subset of models.  The miners there optimize inference on those specific models to an extraordinary degree, e.g. inference times on the flux-1.schnell image generation model are about 65% or so faster than the default pipeline last time I checked (and it's probably faster now than it was then).

Chutes, on the other hand, is meant to be a general purpose compute substrate for *any* AI task, but generally speaking it's code that uses our pre-defined templates, and isn't necessarily optimized by the creator of the "chute" (aka that particular inference endpoint/model), to the Nth degree the way the models get optimized on 19.

On chutes, any user can deploy any model, with any GPU configuration, and the miners will scale it up based on usage.  Chutes is all about providing compute any time for anything. Nineteen is all about extreme optimization on specific models.  In other words, somewhat "breadth vs depth" problem.

To ensure this optimization on 19, they use exponential scoring, and you truly have to provide impeccable networking and optimization to survive as a miner there. On chutes, the goal is more reliability and availability of anything, so we actually normalize scoring by TPS (tokens per second) and SPS (steps per second for diffusion models) since we care more about requests completing successfully than pure speed.

When a model is popular enough and/or needs that extra optimization, it can then be deployed on nineteen as well for a better user experience.

Chutes currently 66 different "chutes", and these also include things nineteen does not provide inference for (transcription, embeddings, video models, etc.), whereas 19 has 13 models currently.

Here, for example, is an extreme illustration of the difference, the performance of the QwQ-32B model.  On chutes, we allow this model to run on many different GPU models, and some are quite slow compared to for example h100 sxm5 nodes.  On nineteen, the miners essentially always use the top-of-the-line hardware for max speed.  On chutes, we can't run every model on premium hardware because the costs would be too high, but on nineteen, by carefully selecting the models to run, you can guarantee max performance on that subset.

Also as to purpose of miners: The miners on nineteen are specialists in optimizing either image models or text generation models.  On chutes, the miners are essentially SREs (site reliability engineers), maintaining thousands of GPUs, uptime, monitoring/etc. The miners on chutes do not need to be AI experts, they need to be system admin/network admin experts, whereas the opposite is true on nineteen. Chutes miners run exactly the code created, and scale according to usage, nineteen miners can modify the code and infra any way they wish so long as it passes validation.

WITH time_series AS (
  SELECT
    generate_series(
      date_trunc('hour', now() - INTERVAL '7 days'),
      date_trunc('hour', now()),
      INTERVAL '1 hour'
    ) AS time_point

-- Get all instances that had at least one successful invocation (ever) while the instance was alive.
instances_with_success AS (
  SELECT DISTINCT
    instance_id
  FROM invocations ii
  WHERE
    error_message IS NULL
    AND completed_at IS NOT NULL
    AND NOT EXISTS (
        SELECT 1
        FROM reports
        WHERE invocation_id = ii.parent_invocation_id
        AND confirmed_at IS NOT NULL
    )
),
-- For each time point, find active instances that have had successful invocations
active_instances_per_timepoint AS (
  SELECT
    ts.time_point,
    ia.instance_id,
    ia.chute_id,
    ia.miner_hotkey
  FROM time_series ts
  JOIN instance_audit ia ON
    ia.verified_at <= ts.time_point AND
    (ia.deleted_at IS NULL OR ia.deleted_at >= ts.time_point)
  JOIN instances_with_success iws ON
    ia.instance_id = iws.instance_id
),
-- Count distinct chute_ids per miner per time point
active_chutes_per_timepoint AS (
  SELECT
    time_point,
    miner_hotkey,
    COUNT(DISTINCT chute_id) AS active_chutes
  FROM active_instances_per_timepoint
  GROUP BY time_point, miner_hotkey
)
-- Calculate average active chutes per miner across all time points
SELECT
  miner_hotkey, time_point,
  AVG(active_chutes)::integer AS avg_active_chutes
FROM active_chutes_per_timepoint where miner_hotkey = 'replaceme'
GROUP BY miner_hotkey, time_point
ORDER BY avg_active_chutes DESC;
```

> CSM (Conversational Speech Model) is a speech generation model from Sesame that generates RVQ audio codes from text and audio inputs. The model architecture employs a Llama backbone and a smaller audio decoder that produces Mimi audio codes.

How is it different from other text-to-speech?  The main difference is that tone/etc. is influenced by previous context, so the previous audio segments influence how the new audio segments are generated, vs just having a completely flat/static output.

Example inference with context.
```python
import os
import requests
import base64

audio = base64.b64encode(open("test.wav", "rb").read()).decode()
result = requests.post(
    "https://chutes-csm-1b.chutes.ai/speak",
    json={
        "speaker": 1,
        "context": [
            {
                "speaker": 0,
                "text": "hello, how are you today? anything on your mind?",
                "audio_b64": audio
            }
        ],
        "text": "Oh I'm fine, thank you, nothing on my mind in particular, how are you?"
    },
    headers={
        "Authorization": os.environ["CHUTES_API_KEY"],
    },
)
with open("new.wav", "wb") as outfile:
    outfile.write(result.content)
```
*Context is not necessary to use the model, you can simply provide a `text` field if you wish*
